o-1 benefit-to-cost ratio.\n\nSPP has provided these benefits during a time of increasingly complex and volatile economic, regulatory and electric industry markets, affecting both the execution planning and resource requirements of SPP and its stakeholders. The initiatives outlined in SPP’s board-adopted Aspire 2026 strategic plan, and the roadmaps reviewed and approved through robust stakeholder processes, continue to be successfully and economically delivered in 2023. SPP forecasts ending the year 6.3% under budget on its Net Revenue Requirement (NRR), or $11.7 million in savings to budget for members.\n\nSPP anticipates the need for additional investments in people, processes and tools in 2024 to address the ever-growing opportunities, risks and challenges facing the organization and the electric industry. Net of an estimated over-recovery of $10.3 million, SPP has budgeted $192.1 million in 2024 NRR. This 11.2% increase reflects compensation, outside services and other operating expense inflationary impacts, incremental headcount additions to build essential organizational capabilities and capacity and consulting support on key engineering and information technology initiatives. Western expansion efforts have discrete contractual commitments that either positively impact SPP’s NRR on a net revenue to cost basis (Markets+), or will be debt financed (RTO West) and have no impact to member NRR through the implementation period.\n\nTransmission usage has steadily grown across SPP’s footprint as well, resulting in a 2% increase from the prior budget period and estimated billing determinants of 418.8 TWh. When calculated against SPP’s 2024 budget NRR, these assumed billing determinants yield an effective administrative fee of $0.459 in 2024. Additional capital investments of $21.2 million will provide long-term capability needs and requisite improvements to aging infrastructure.\n\nThe growing complexity and volatility of the markets SPP operates in, coupled with important initiatives mandated or approved by its stakeholders and board, results in some exciting opportunities and challenges for SPP. The organization plans to deploy expert resources\n\n2024 BUDGET SOUTHWEST POWER POOL PAGE 5 effectively and efficiently in 2024 to continue delivering on its commitment to responsibly and economically keep the lights on, today and in the future.\n\nII. BUDGET OVERVIEW\n\nBACKGROUND \nThe 2024 Operating Plan served as a guide for budget development, with the \nOperating Plan in turn based on the 2021-2026 strategic plan Aspire 2026 and \ncurrent corporate objectives. \n\nSPP’s officers met in June 2023 to recommend the 2024 corporate and departmental strategic objectives for the organization. These objectives then guided the departmental execution plans described in the 2024 Operating Plan, ultimately forming the basis for the resource requirements included in the 2024-2026 budget. SPP utilized both zero-based and incremental based budget approaches to determine the appropriate department-level operating expenses needed to deliver the plan. See below for the planning approach utilized by SPP in 2024.\n\n2024 BUDGET SOUTHWEST POWER POOL PAGE 6\n\nOperating expenses represent the largest component of SPP’s NRR and comprise budgeted costs for ongoing operations. Budgets for departmental operating expenses were reviewed and approved by their respective directors and executives. SPP required explanations for significant changes from the 2023 forecast. The executive team reviewed and approved the consolidated results. The Resource Utilization section of this document discusses material changes from the 2023 forecast in detail.\n\nCapital expenditures are investments in long-term assets required by SPP to meet its strategic goals and operational requirements. These capital expenditures represent costs incurred to enhance or expand current systems and services and/or maintain existing capabilities. SPP staff and management review and track foundation and capital project expenditures, and approve new projects through a multi-layered internal committee process. The foundation budget captures hardware and software investments required to support SPP’s business applications. This includes upgrades and replacements of SPP’s aging hardware infrastructure and expenditures for new enterprise technologies, driven by security requirements, application and architectural enhancements, and legacy growth. Capital projects are generally specific initiatives to expand or meaningfully enhance SPP’s product and service offerings.\n\nDebt service costs are principal payments and interest expenses related to various borrowings obtained to fund SPP’s capital expenditures. The debt issuances have terms relatively consistent with the expected useful life of the assets developed or acquired, which is consistent with SPP’s longstanding financing policy. This policy is in place to recover the cost of the assets from the customers who benefit from them over the period of the assets’ useful life.\n\nThe combined efforts of identifying required operating expenses and the planning and funding for capital projects resulted in a recommended NRR of $192.1 million in 2024. This amount represents a total NRR increase of $19.3 million and a $16.9 million increase for run-rate NRR compared to the 2023 forecast. Increasing labor costs, driven by both inflationary (price) and staffing capacity and capability needs (volume), is the main driver for the 2024 budget vs. 2023 forecast NRR increase. Section IV provides more detailed information on these budgeted investments in SPP resources.\n\nOPERATING PLAN \nSPP’s 2024 Operating Plan describes the major work SPP will undertake to \nachieve the SPP strategic plan, Aspire 2026, operate the organization and carry \nout its mission. \n\nThe 2024 Operating Plan describes the organizational execution plans and operating activities required to achieve SPP’s 2024 strategic priorities. The plan was developed to identify and recognize which departmental goals and initiatives are required to enable SPP",
